    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm running a linear regression on some housing price data and I'm seeing some weirdness with my residuals. They don't look normally distributed at all—lots of outliers and a heavy skew. What's the best way to handle this so my model stays valid?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have a few options for dealing with non-normal residuals, but first, you should check if your model assumptions are being violated by something more fundamental, like a missing variable or a lurking variable. If the residuals are truly skewed and have heavy outliers, you might consider transforming your dependent variable or the residuals themselves.\n\nTransforming the dependent variable, perhaps using a log transformation, can often help normalize the error term. If the data is heavily skewed, a log transform is a good first step. You can also try using a more robust regression technique, like a robust linear regression method, which are less sensitive to outliers.",
      "source": "target",
