    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Does a log transformation always work though? I'm worried that if the skew is really extreme, the transform won't be enough to fix the distribution. Are there other ways to look at the errors, maybe something involving the variance or the way the outliers are spreading out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A log transformation isn't a magic bullet, and if the skew is truly extreme, you might need something stronger. You can try Box-Cox transformations, which are a family of power transformations that automatically finds the best power to use to stabilize the variance and normalize the distribution.\n\nAlternatively, instead of focusing solely on the distribution, you can look at robust estimation methods. Techniques like M-estimation or using a Huber loss function in your regression can down-weight the influence of those extreme outliers. This keeps the core of your data intact while ignoring the noisy, outlying data points.",
      "source": "target",
