    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. What if the outliers aren't just random noise, but actually represent some underlying pattern that's being ignored? Like if there's a specific subset of properties causing all this variance and making the residuals look so messy. How would I identify if these outliers are actually meaningful or just errors?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If those outliers are actually meaningful, you're looking at a potential structural issue, not just a statistical blip. You should start by visually inspecting the data points corresponding to those large residuals. Look at the original housing data—are these properties in a specific neighborhood, have unique features (like being brand new or unusually large), or belong to a certain class?\n\nYou could try segmenting your data. Run separate regressions on different subsets of the data. If the residuals look much cleaner in one subset than another, you've found your pattern. This is a good way to see if the variance is being driven by a specific group of properties.",
      "source": "target",
